	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Charleston S.C.</placeName> <date>April 20<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1830</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Revd. Mr. Leeser</addressee>&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">My Dear Sir&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">I was not misrepresented to you<lb/> when you were told I entertain &#8220;feelings of Friendship&#59;&#8221;<lb/> and I am pleased in the opportunity thus offered&#44; of<lb/> renewing to you&#44; the assurance of the most unfeigned<lb/> sentiments of Friendly concern&#44; for your prosperity and<lb/> advancement&#44; without using high toned expressions&#44; you<lb/> have claims to the regard of every man who<lb/> venerates the religion of his forefathers&#44; and your<lb/> individual merits entitle you to the consideration<lb/> of those who possess your acquaintance.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I shall cheerfully use my efforts to further<lb/> your views in obtaining subscribers to your contemplated<lb/> Publications&#44; and doubt not they will meet with<lb/> deserved approbation.  I have placed one of<lb/> the Properties in the hands of a respectable book<lb/> seller who will use all exertions to obtain subscribers<lb/> not of our <sic>pursuasion</sic>&#8212;and he intends also to make<lb/> it more public by placing it in the Gazette of our<lb/> city&#44; provided it is agreeable to you.  I cannot<lb/> promise you many subscribers among our people.<lb/>  I find that the subscription lists you sent<lb/> to other of your Friends are in circulation&#44; and<lb/> will interfere with the number of subscribers&#44; the</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>I should have otherwise obtained&#8212;however&#44; I<lb/> shall do all I can for you.  Why was your title<lb/> of Revd not prefixed to your name&#63;  I hope your<lb/> modesty did not prompt to the omissions.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">It is sometime since I have heard from<lb/> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#44; it is always a source of pleasure to<lb/> hear of my Friends through any channel.  I hope<lb/> they are all well particularly the young Ladies&#44;<lb/> to whom you will please make my best respects<lb/> acceptable.  By&#45;the&#45;By&#44; have you made a selection&#63;<lb/> <sic>and</sic> is your admiration of the Lady you name<lb/> in your letter&#44; still as strong as when I last was<lb/> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#63;  I have always considered it as<lb/> perfectly consistent with clerical Gentlemen&#44; to pay their<lb/> adorations to a superior and Inferior <hi rend="underline">Divinities</hi>.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I contemplate&#44; should professional concerns not<lb/> interfere&#44; to pay you a short visit some time during<lb/> the summer&#44; till which I have the pleasure</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">of subscribing myself</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">your friend and</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)">well wisher</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Jacob De La Motta</persName></p>
				<p>P. S. My best respects to<lb/> <persName>Mr. Peixotto</persName> and his family.</p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p>The <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
				<p>per packet</p>
				<p><persName>Langdon Chaves<add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
